      <p class="article-meta">Published March 5, 2026 · By ToolCalcs Team</p>
      <h1>How Much Paint Do I Need? A Room-by-Room Guide</h1>
      <p class="article-intro">Buying too much paint wastes money. Buying too little means a second trip to the store and the risk that your batch won't match. Whether you are refreshing a single bedroom or painting an entire house, here is how to calculate exactly how much paint you need before you open a single can.</p>
    </header>

    <section>
      <h2>The Basic Formula</h2>
      <p>Every paint calculation starts with the same straightforward formula:</p>
      <p><strong>Paintable wall area = (room perimeter x ceiling height) &minus; doors &minus; windows</strong></p>
      <p>To find the perimeter, add the lengths of all four walls. For a rectangular room, that is simply two times the length plus two times the width. Multiply that perimeter by the ceiling height to get the total wall surface area. Then subtract the areas you will not be painting, primarily doors and windows.</p>
      <p>Standard deductions to remember:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Door</strong> &mdash; approximately 21 square feet (3 ft x 7 ft)</li>
        <li><strong>Window</strong> &mdash; approximately 15 square feet (3 ft x 5 ft, varies by size)</li>
      </ul>
      <p>Once you have the total paintable area in square feet, you can use our <a href="/construction-calculators/paint-calculator/">Paint Calculator</a> to get an instant answer, or keep reading to do the math yourself.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Paint Coverage Rates</h2>
      <p>A single gallon of paint does not cover the same area in every situation. The type of paint, the finish, and the surface you are applying it to all change the coverage rate. Here are the numbers you can expect under normal conditions:</p>

      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>Paint Type / Surface</th>
            <th>Coverage per Gallon</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>Latex (smooth drywall)</td><td>350&ndash;400 sq ft</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Latex (textured wall)</td><td>250&ndash;350 sq ft</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Oil-based (smooth surface)</td><td>350&ndash;400 sq ft</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Primer (new drywall)</td><td>200&ndash;300 sq ft</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Primer (previously painted)</td><td>300&ndash;350 sq ft</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Ceiling paint (flat finish)</td><td>350&ndash;400 sq ft</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Exterior paint (wood siding)</td><td>250&ndash;350 sq ft</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Exterior paint (smooth stucco)</td><td>150&ndash;250 sq ft</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>

      <p>For most interior projects on smooth, previously painted drywall, plan on roughly 350 square feet per gallon. If your walls have a knockdown or orange-peel texture, drop that estimate to around 300 square feet per gallon because the texture absorbs more paint.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Step-by-Step Calculation Example</h2>
      <p>Let's walk through a real scenario. Suppose you are painting a bedroom that measures 12 feet by 14 feet with 9-foot ceilings. The room has one standard door and two average-sized windows.</p>

      <h3>Step 1: Calculate the Perimeter</h3>
      <p>Perimeter = (12 + 14) x 2 = <strong>52 feet</strong></p>

      <h3>Step 2: Calculate the Total Wall Area</h3>
      <p>Total wall area = 52 ft x 9 ft = <strong>468 square feet</strong></p>

      <h3>Step 3: Subtract Doors and Windows</h3>
      <p>Door: 1 x 21 sq ft = 21 sq ft</p>
      <p>Windows: 2 x 15 sq ft = 30 sq ft</p>
      <p>Paintable wall area = 468 &minus; 21 &minus; 30 = <strong>417 square feet</strong></p>

      <h3>Step 4: Divide by Coverage Rate</h3>
      <p>Using a standard coverage rate of 350 sq ft per gallon:</p>
      <p>417 / 350 = <strong>1.19 gallons per coat</strong></p>

      <h3>Step 5: Multiply by Number of Coats</h3>
      <p>Most paint jobs need two coats (more on that below):</p>
      <p>1.19 x 2 = <strong>2.38 gallons total</strong></p>
      <p>In practice, you would buy <strong>3 gallons</strong> to ensure you have enough with a small margin for touch-ups. If you want to skip the arithmetic, plug your room dimensions into our <a href="/construction-calculators/paint-calculator/">Paint Calculator</a> and it handles every step automatically.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Room-by-Room Quick Reference</h2>
      <p>Not everyone wants to measure every wall. The table below gives you practical estimates for common room sizes, assuming standard 8-foot ceilings, one door per room, an average number of windows, and two coats of latex paint on smooth drywall.</p>

      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>Room</th>
            <th>Typical Size</th>
            <th>Approx. Wall Area</th>
            <th>Paint Needed (2 coats)</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>Small bedroom</td><td>10 x 10 ft</td><td>280 sq ft</td><td>2 gallons</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Average bedroom</td><td>12 x 12 ft</td><td>340 sq ft</td><td>2 gallons</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Large bedroom</td><td>14 x 16 ft</td><td>420 sq ft</td><td>3 gallons</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Master bedroom</td><td>16 x 18 ft</td><td>490 sq ft</td><td>3 gallons</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Bathroom</td><td>5 x 8 ft</td><td>170 sq ft</td><td>1 gallon</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Large bathroom</td><td>8 x 10 ft</td><td>240 sq ft</td><td>1&ndash;2 gallons</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Living room</td><td>15 x 20 ft</td><td>500 sq ft</td><td>3 gallons</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Large living room</td><td>18 x 24 ft</td><td>620 sq ft</td><td>4 gallons</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Kitchen</td><td>10 x 12 ft</td><td>280 sq ft</td><td>2 gallons</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Dining room</td><td>12 x 14 ft</td><td>350 sq ft</td><td>2 gallons</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Hallway (8 ft long)</td><td>4 x 8 ft</td><td>150 sq ft</td><td>1 gallon</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>

      <p>These are ballpark figures. Your actual numbers will vary based on ceiling height, window count, and wall texture. For a precise answer based on your exact measurements, use the <a href="/everyday-calculators/square-footage-calculator/">Square Footage Calculator</a> to measure your wall area, then apply the formula above.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>When You Need Extra Paint</h2>
      <p>Some situations demand more paint than the standard formula suggests. Watch for these common scenarios:</p>

      <h3>Dark-to-Light Color Changes</h3>
      <p>Painting over a dark wall with a lighter color is one of the biggest paint traps. Standard two coats may not fully hide the old color. You could end up needing three or even four coats if you skip a tinted primer. The smarter approach is to apply one coat of a gray or tinted primer that is close to your new color, then follow with two coats of your finish paint. This uses less total paint and gives better results than layering on extra topcoats.</p>

      <h3>Textured Walls</h3>
      <p>Knockdown, orange peel, popcorn, and other textured finishes have more surface area than flat drywall. Expect to use 15 to 25 percent more paint on textured surfaces. Heavy textures like popcorn ceilings can use up to 50 percent more than the label suggests.</p>

      <h3>New or Unprimed Drywall</h3>
      <p>Fresh drywall is porous and absorbs paint like a sponge. Always apply a dedicated primer first. Skipping primer on new drywall does not save money because you will need extra coats of expensive finish paint to compensate, and the final result will look uneven.</p>

      <h3>Porous Surfaces</h3>
      <p>Bare wood, brick, and cinder block all absorb more paint than sealed surfaces. A coat of primer designed for the specific material will reduce overall paint consumption and produce a more uniform finish.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Ceiling and Trim Calculations</h2>
      <p>Walls are only part of the picture. If you are painting the ceiling or trim, you need to account for those separately.</p>

      <h3>Ceilings</h3>
      <p>Ceiling area is simply the room's length times its width. For a 12 x 14 foot room, the ceiling is 168 square feet. At 350 to 400 square feet per gallon, one gallon of ceiling paint will cover most standard rooms in a single coat. Ceilings typically need only one coat unless you are making a significant color change.</p>

      <h3>Trim, Baseboards, and Door Frames</h3>
      <p>Trim paint (usually semi-gloss or high-gloss) covers roughly the same square footage per gallon, but the area is much smaller. A rough estimate: measure the total linear feet of trim and multiply by the trim width (typically 3.5 to 5.5 inches). For most rooms, one quart of trim paint is sufficient. For an entire house, plan on one to two gallons. Don't forget to include window casings, door frames, and crown molding in your measurements.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>How Many Coats Do You Actually Need?</h2>
      <p>The short answer: two coats in most cases. Here is a more detailed breakdown:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>One coat</strong> &mdash; Only realistic when painting the same color over itself for a simple refresh, or when using a high-quality paint-and-primer-in-one product over a similar shade.</li>
        <li><strong>Two coats</strong> &mdash; The standard for any color change. Two coats provide even coverage, consistent color, and better durability. This is what paint manufacturers assume when they print coverage rates on the can.</li>
        <li><strong>Three or more coats</strong> &mdash; Necessary when covering very dark colors with light ones (without primer), painting bright reds or yellows that have poor hiding power, or working on extremely porous surfaces.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>Spending the time on two proper coats saves you from uneven patches, visible roller marks, and the frustration of a paint job that looks fine in some light but terrible in others. Let each coat dry fully before applying the next. Most latex paints need at least two to four hours between coats.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Tips for Buying the Right Amount</h2>
      <p>Armed with your square footage calculation, here are some practical rules for making the purchase:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Add 10 percent extra.</strong> This is the golden rule. If your math says you need 2.5 gallons, buy 3. That 10 percent accounts for drips, roller absorption, touch-ups, and slightly uneven application. You will almost always use more paint than the formula predicts.</li>
        <li><strong>Buy all your paint at once.</strong> Paint is mixed in batches, and even the same color code can vary slightly between batches. Buying everything in one trip ensures consistent color across every wall.</li>
        <li><strong>Round up, not down.</strong> Paint comes in quarts and gallons. If your calculation lands at 1.3 gallons, buy two gallons rather than one gallon and one quart. The extra half gallon gives you a comfortable buffer and costs less than a separate quart.</li>
        <li><strong>Keep leftover paint.</strong> Store unused paint in a sealed container for future touch-ups. Label it with the room name, color code, and date. Leftover paint is invaluable when you need to fix a scuff mark or patch a nail hole six months from now.</li>
        <li><strong>Check the return policy.</strong> Most home improvement stores accept returns on unopened, unmixed paint. Buy an extra gallon if you are uncertain and return it if you don't crack the lid.</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>The Bottom Line</h2>
      <p>Calculating paint quantities is not complicated once you know the formula. Measure your walls, subtract doors and windows, divide by the coverage rate, multiply by the number of coats, and add 10 percent. For a typical 12 x 14 foot bedroom with 9-foot ceilings, that works out to about 3 gallons for two coats on the walls.</p>
      <p>The biggest mistakes people make are underestimating how much paint textured surfaces absorb and skipping primer when changing colors dramatically. Both lead to extra trips to the store and uneven results. Take the time to assess your surfaces before you buy, apply primer when the situation calls for it, and always round up.</p>
